        <h1>Policy Checks Workflow</h1>
        <p>The typical Liquibase policy checks workflow looks as follows:</p>
        <p>DBAs, Architects, Developers and others in your organization may have set specific standards for database changes and security roles. Liquibase policy checks can be configured (copied, customized, enabled, disabled) on the command line to meet these standards, which are stored in an auto-generated configuration file called <code>liquibase-checks-settings.conf</code>. Your organization's teams can have multiple configuration files.</p>
        <p>Next, a team obtains configuration files for a specific project from source code control. It is best practice to keep the checks configuration with the changelog in source code control so that it is delivered to anyone who works with the changelog.</p>
        <p>Then, from the command line, you can navigate to the location of the Liquibasechangelog and configuration files and run <code>checks</code> commands to configure and execute checks. For more information, see .</p>
        <p>Changes, such as new copies, customizations, enabled status, and disabled status, are saved in the checks settings file, which you can commit to source control to be used in development, on-demand, and automated policy checks executions.</p>
